'''Ricardo de la Cierva y Hoces''' (9 November 1926 – 19 November 2015) was a Spanish historian and politician.
A native of Madrid, de la Cierva served the constituency of [[Murcia (Spanish Congress Electoral District)|Murcia]] in the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Congress of Deputies]] and [[Senate of Spain|Senate]] from 1977 to 1982. He was the [[Ministry of Culture (Spain)|Minister of Culture]] for nine months in 1980. Originally a member of the [[Union of the Democratic Centre (Spain)|Union of the Democratic Centre]], de la Cierva switched to the [[People's Alliance (Spain)|People's Alliance]] in February 1982, then stepped down from the [[Cortes Generales]] upon the end of his term in August of that year. De la Cierva won the second prize of the 1988 [[Premio Planeta de Novela]], and also wrote for the magazine ''[[Época (Spanish magazine)|Época]]''. He died in 2015.<ref>[http://cultura.elpais.com/cultura/2015/11/19/actualidad/1447950708_710699.html Muere el historiador franquista Ricardo de la Cierva] {{es icon}}</ref>
